# Documentation

**basin** is a numerical optimization library for Rust. It follows the overall
shape of [argmin](https://argmin-rs.org): a generic *executor* loop drives a
*solver* over a *state*, calling into the *problem* traits you implement
(`CostFunction`, `Gradient`, and friends).

> **Alpha.** The public API is still iterating and breaking changes are
> expected. Pin a version and read the changelog before upgrading.

## How the pieces fit

- **Problem** — what you implement. A `CostFunction` (and a `Gradient`, if your
  solver needs one) describing the objective. Constraints such as box bounds
  live here too, not on the solver.
- **Solver** — the algorithm. Gradient descent, Nelder–Mead, L-BFGS,
  Levenberg–Marquardt, CMA-ES, and more.
- **State** — the iterate(s) a solver carries: a single point (`BasicState`),
  a simplex (`BasicSimplexState`), a population, and so on.
- **Executor** — the driver that runs a solver to termination and hands back an
  `OptimizationResult`.
- **Termination** — pluggable stopping criteria (gradient/parameter/cost
  tolerances, iteration and time budgets) configured uniformly across solvers.

## Where to go next

- [Getting started](getting-started/) — install basin and run your first solve.
- [Solvers](solvers/) — the catalogue of solvers and which backends they need.

You can also watch solvers converge interactively in the
[visualizer](../visualizer/), or browse the full API on
[docs.rs](https://docs.rs/basin).
